The paper proposes a composite approach to real-time traffic control using sensed information and scheduling decisions, which involves modeling successive movement phases as different states of an Ising model. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Multiagent Systems (cs.MA) or Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper involves the use of artificial intelligence techniques to compute weights for vehicle clusters, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also involves the exchange of information between direct neighbors, which suggests that it may belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of a model to quantify the strength of interactions, which suggests that it may also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
